The possible interferences of other metal ions were evaluated by competitive experiments. The change in fluorescence intensity of S1 in S2 solution was measured by adding 10 equiv of Fe3+ ions and 10 equiv of other interfering metal ions, including Ba2+, Cd2+, Mg2+, Na+, Ni2+, Sr2+, Al3+, Ca2+, Cu2+, K+, Mn2+, NH4
                           +, Pb2+, Zn2+, Fe2+, and Li+. The results show that fluorescence quenching still occurred in the presence of other metal ions (Fig. 9
                           ). This observation confirmed that the quenching effect of Fe3+ on S1 is not affected by other coexist metal ions.

Fig. 12
 shows the spectrogram of the optical fiber sensor in different concentrations of Fe3+ solutions at room temperature. With the increase of Fe3+ concentration, there is a significant blue shift of the interference peak. The distance of blue shift is linear with iron ion concentration, and the fitting coefficient is 0.9985. Considering that the spectrometer has a resolution of 0.02, the detection limit of iron ion is calculated to be 1.37 × 10−10 M. Compared with S1 for detecting Fe3+ in S2 solution, the construction of S1-based fiber optic sensor reduces the detection limit of Fe3+ by several orders of magnitude, the sensor can detect extremely low concentrations of Fe3+. Compared with other fluorescence methods for detecting iron ions, the detection limit of our technique has obvious advantage (Table 1
). To the standard for iron content in drinking water (300 μg/L, the World Health Organization), the sensor can fully meet the requirements of measurement. In general, the optical fiber sensor fabricated in this paper has the advantages of high selectivity, high detection limit, easy operation and remote monitoring.
